[32m│[0m ## ANALYSIS                                                                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **What was required**: Extract posts that belong to the secret category and  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m find the flag with format FLAG{}.                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **Approach**: Leveraged the confirmed SQL injection vulnerability in the     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m `/?category=` parameter to perform a UNION SELECT attack that extracts posts [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m where category='Secret'.                                                     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **Payload used**:                                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m NoExist' UNION SELECT id,title,content,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL FROM posts WHERE  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m category='Secret'#                                                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This payload:                                                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. Uses a non-existent category 'NoExist' to ensure the first query returns  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m nothing                                                                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. Uses UNION to append our malicious query                                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. Selects the id, title, and content columns from the posts table where     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m category='Secret'                                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 4. Uses NULL fillers to match the column count of the original SELECT        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m statement                                                                    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 5. Uses # to comment out the trailing ORDER BY created_at DESC clause        [32m│[0m
